# Secrets (agenix)

All `.age` files here are `age` ciphertext, encrypted to the recipients declared
per-file in `secrets.nix`. Plaintext never enters git or the world-readable
/nix/store; agenix decrypts at activation into a tmpfs (/run/agenix or the
home-manager user runtime dir). agenix is the right tool for this fleet and is
used idiomatically — see memory/findings/agenix-fit-verdict-research.md.

## Two scopes (this is the intended agenix design, not a workaround)

- PERSONAL scope — decrypted by the home-manager agenix module using the user
  key `~/.ssh/id_ed25519`. Session-gated. Recipients: `userKeys` only.
  Surfaces only where the personal key file exists (the macOS m3pro host; in
  devcontainers you `gh auth login` at runtime instead). These NEVER decrypt on
  a server — by design (age has no ssh-agent support; a server has no personal
  key file). Example: github-token.age → GH_TOKEN.

- HOST scope — decrypted by the NixOS system agenix during activation using the
  host key `/etc/ssh/ssh_host_ed25519_key`, before login and before
  multi-user.target services. Recipients: `userKeys ++ [ <host> ]` (the user key
  so you can re-encrypt; the host key so the server decrypts at boot).
  Example: nixbox-tunnel-creds.age.

## Encrypt / re-encrypt

    agenix -e secrets/<name>.age          # idiomatic (needs a recipient's private key)

Without nix/agenix on the Mac, use plain age to ALL recipients:

    age -r "<userKey>" [-r "<host pubkey>"] -o secrets/<name>.age < plaintext

Round-trip verify by sha256 (never echo the value). Commit the resulting `.age`.

## Per-host scoped-down token (a server that needs a token)

Do NOT put the broad personal PAT or your personal private key on a server.
Instead mint a fine-grained, minimal-privilege, short-expiry token for that host
and encrypt it to the HOST key — just another host-scoped secret, no new tooling:

  1. Create a fine-grained token scoped to the minimum that host needs.
  2. secrets.nix:  "<host>-<svc>-token.age".publicKeys = userKeys ++ [ <host> ];
  3. Encrypt it (above), commit the `.age`.
  4. Wire it in hosts/<host>.nix:  age.secrets.<name> = { file = "${secretsDir}/<host>-<svc>-token.age"; mode = "0400"; owner = "..."; };
     and consume config.age.secrets.<name>.path from the service.

## HAZARD — host-key rotation silently breaks host-scoped secrets

SSH keys double as age identities. Replacing a host's
/etc/ssh/ssh_host_ed25519_key (reinstall, reimage, rotation) makes every
host-scoped `.age` undecryptable at next activation, with no loud error until the
service fails. After ANY host-key change, re-run the agenix-host-rekey skill for
that host and rebuild. The personal key carries the same caveat for the personal
scope (re-encrypt all userKeys secrets with `agenix -r`).

## Build-time-only material

nixbox-hostkey.age holds a PINNED host PRIVATE key (encrypted to userKeys) used
ONLY to inject a host identity into a prebuilt image (skill:
nixbox-prebake-hostkey). It is deliberately NOT wired into any host's
age.secrets — never add it there.
